  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  A mother is 20years older than his second son. The sum of their ages is 48years. Find their ages.
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  Let the son’s age = x
  <br>
  Mother’s age = x + 20
  <br>
  x + (x + 20) = 48
  <br>
  x + x + 20 = 48
  <br>
  2x + 20 = 48
  <br>
  2x = 48 – 20
  <br> 
  2x = 28 divide both sides by 2
  <br>
  <sup>2x</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub> = <sup>28</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub>
  <br>
  X = 14
  <br>
  Therefore;
  <br>
  The son’s age = <strong>14</strong> 
  <br>
  The mother’s age is (x + 20) = (14 + 20) = <strong>34years</strong>
  </div>
  <div class="col">
  <strong>Example 2</strong>
  <br>
  The sum of Smith’s age and John’s age is 25years. 8years ago, Smith’s age was twice as old as John’s age. How old are they now?
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  Let Smith’s age = S
  <br>
  Let John’s age = J
  <br>
  S + J = 25-----------(1)
  <br>
  S – 8 = 2(J – 8)
  <br>
  S – 8 = 2J – 16 
  <br>
  S = 2J – 16 + 8
  <br>
  S = 2J – 8 ---------------(2)
  <br>
  Substitute equation (2) in equation (1)
  <br>
  S + J = 25
  <br>
  2J – 8 + J = 25
  <br>
  3J = 25 + 8
  <br>
  3J = 33; divide both sides by 3
  <br>
  <sup>3J</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub> = <sup>33</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>
  <br>
  J = 11
  Substitute J in equation (1)
  S + J = 25
  <br>
  S + 11 = 25
  <br>
  S = 25 – 11
  <br>
  S = 14
  <br>
  Therefore;
  <br>
   Smith’s age = <strong>14years</strong>
   <br>
   John’s age = <strong>11years.</strong>
  </div>
