  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>How to Solve Simultaneous Equation with Substitution Method</h3>
  </div>
  <strong>Substitution</strong> method is commonly used when the coefficient of one of the unknowns in the given equations is 1.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Use substitution method to solve this pair of simultaneous equations; x + y = 4 and 2x – y = 5.
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
    x + y = 4 --------------------(1)
  <br>
    2x – y = 5 ------------------ (2)
  <br>
  From equation (1);
  <br>
  y = 4 ─ x ---------------(3)
  <br>
  Substitute equation (3) in equation (2)
  <br>
  2x ─ (4 ─ x) = 5; open up the bracket and collect like terms.
  <br>
  2x – 4 + x = 5
  <br>
  2x + x – 4 = 5
  <br>
  3x – 4 = 5
  <br>
  3x = 5 + 4
  <br>
  3x = 9; divide by 3
  <br>
  <sup>3x</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub> = <sup>9</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>
  <br>
  x = 3
  <br>
  Substitute value of x in either of the equation (1) or equation (2).
  <br>
  x + y = 4; when x = 3
  <br>
  3 + y = 4
  <br>
  y = 4 – 3 
  <br>
  y = 1
  <br>
  Therefore, when x = 3, y = 1
  <br>  
  Check;
  <br>
  x + y = 4; when x = 3, y =1
  <br>
  3 + 1 = 4
  <br>
  4 = 4 (LHS = RHS; the answers are true)
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Solve Simultaneous Equations with Elimination Methods</h3>
  </div>
  <strong>Elimination</strong> method is commonly used when <strong>none</strong> of the coefficients of the unknowns in the given equations is 1. Elimination is simply done by getting rid of one of the unknowns through making its coefficient the same in both equations, then <strong>add</strong> or <strong>subtract</strong> the two equations as necessary.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Use elimination method to solve this pair of simultaneous equations; <strong>3a – 2b = 4</strong> and <strong>2a + 3b = ─6.</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	3a – 2b = 4 -----------------------(1)
  <br>
  (ii)	2a + 3b = ─6 ----------------------(2)
  <br>
  The coefficient of <strong>a</strong> can be made the same by multiplying equation (1) with 2 and equation (2) with 3.
  <br>
  2 x 3a – 2b = 4
  <br>
  3 x 2a + 3b = ─6
  <br>
  <strong>It becomes;</strong>
  <br>
  <span class='ml-5'>6a – 4b = 8 </span>
  <br>
  ─ (<span class='ml-4'>6a + 9b = ─18</span> )
  <br>
  <span class='ml-3'> -------------------------------------</span>
  <br>
  <span class='ml-5'> -13b = 26 ;</span> <span class='ml-3'>─13b = ─4b ─(9b) and 26 = 8 ─(─18)</span>
  <br>
  <sup>-13b</sup>&frasl;<sub>-13</sub> = <sup>26</sup>&frasl;<sub>-13</sub> divide both sides by ─13
  <br>
  b = ─2
  <br>
  Substitute the value of b in equation (2)
  <br>
  3a – 2b = 4
  <br>
  3a – 2(─2) = 4
  <br>
  3a + 4 = 4
  <br>
  3a = 4 – 4 
  <br>
  3a = 0 divide both sides by 3
  <br>
  <sup>3a</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>  = <sup>0</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>
  <br>
  a = 0
  <br>
  Therefore; a = 0 and b = -2
  <br>
  Check;
  <br>
  3a – 2b = 4; when a = 0, b = −2
  <br>
  3(0) – 2(−2) = 4
  <br>
  0 + 4 = 4
  <br>
  +4 = 4 (LHS = RHS; the answers are true)
  <br>
  <strong>Example 2</strong>
  <br>
  Use elimination method to solve this simultaneous equations; <strong>2x + 5y = 0</strong> and <strong>3x – 2y = 19.</strong>
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
